ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the research findings regarding materials, system changes, and microbial structure, we attempt to reveal the potential mechanisms through which these CQD promote high-load AD (Fig. 10
                        ). Different CQD with smaller particle sizes can support their binding to microbial surfaces. These CQD were rich in functional groups (C-O-C and C-O-H) capable of binding with NH4
                        +, thereby mitigating the inhibition of ammonia nitrogen on microbes. Furthermore, these CQD can be endocytosed by microorganisms. Upon internalization, they stimulated physiological responses in microbes, promoting redox metabolism. This viewpoint was supported by Yang et al. and Liu et al. [25,53]. This mechanism was defined as shielding and endocytosis. In addition, these CQD possessed good conductivity and water solubility, providing conditions for the formation of conductive networks in AD systems [24]. This conductive network served as a carrier for enriching electroactive bacteria (such as Clostridium) and accelerating electron transfer in the system. The efficiency of DIET in AD systems was further enhanced. In summary, through improving the microbial surface environment and constructing electron transfer network, these CQD significantly enhanced the performance of AD systems.
